# Post-mortem -- slice 007, attempt 01

## Summary

Slice 007 (the final slice of arc 0026) escalated on the failures cap with all seven gates green: the code-judge returned `route-back-to-worker` twice over the same narrow defect -- the no-op snapshot-push guard is still not uniform (`resetRotationNow` and `setPrimaryDetectorNow` keep the unconditional `commit`) while the SoW asserts it is. The cheap re-spawn the judge explicitly expected never happened because an earlier worker exit-1 crash had already consumed a failure slot and forced the slice's single resolver run early, so the per-slice resolver cap was spent and the supervisor escalated instead of re-spawning.

## Root cause

The single load-bearing cause is an **incomplete execution of the cycle-1 review steer, paired with a state-of-the-world that over-claims the fix**. Cycle 1 asked the worker to "make the no-op guard uniform" so that an inert edit pushes no empty `Ctrl+Z` step (the slice's own named High risk, AC-K1). Attempt 03 fixed the one site cycle 1 named -- `editActive` now routes through `commitIfChanged` (`ConstructorView.fs:208`, verified) -- and genuinely closed the second cycle-1 finding by exposing `SchemaValidation.collectMessages` and calling it from `GroupsLibrary.validate` (`GroupsLibrary.fs:66`). But two sibling commit sites were left on the unconditional `commit`: `resetRotationNow` (`ConstructorView.fs:350`, verified `commit (setPlacement i { p with r1 = Angle.zero; ... })`) and `setPrimaryDetectorNow` (`ConstructorView.fs:435`, verified `commit { model with ... }`). Reset-rotation is confirmation-gated but armed regardless of the element's current rotation, so confirming it on an already-zero element runs `setPlacement` with no change yet still pushes an identical snapshot -- the exact empty-`Ctrl+Z` step the cycle-1 fix removed, on a different path; `setPrimaryDetectorNow` is the same class in the index-0 case where `moveToFront 0` is identity. Meanwhile the SoW asserts "The guard is now UNIFORM" (`007-state-of-the-world.md:80`), naming only `editActive`, the arrow-key slide and the slide drag -- a claim the diff contradicts. Both the code-judge (`007-03-code-judge.md`) and the architecture critic (`007-01-architecture-critic.md`) flagged this residual independently; the judge's deciding factor was that on the arc's **final** slice, which carries the closing baseline, a SoW that overstates the very property the review loop has gated across two cycles should not be rubber-stamped when the remedy is the identical one already applied to `editActive`.

The **mechanical cause of escalation** (rather than another re-spawn) is a prematurely exhausted failure budget. The judge sized this as "one cheap re-spawn away" with `cycles_remaining = 1`, expecting another worker cycle -- but the per-slice failures cap tripped first. The first worker run on this slice crashed: `idx=6 count=1/2: worker exited non-zero (exit=1) without arc-runner intervention` (log line 511), consuming a failure slot with a non-review crash unrelated to any finding. The cycle-1 route-back then hit `count=2/2` (log 557); the slice's single resolver run (run 1) rescued that premature cap, noting it explicitly, and consumed the per-slice resolver budget (`resolver_runs` now 1/1). When the cycle-2 route-back arrived it pushed `idx=6 count=3/3` (log 611), and with the resolver cap already spent the supervisor logged `RESOLVER-SKIP` and escalated. So the substantive defect kept the judge routing back, but it was the crash-inflated failures cap plus the already-consumed resolver run that converted a genuinely-trivial fix into an escalation.

